    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i see. so if the goal is just to stick to what the text meant back then, how do people handle cases where the original meaning would obviously lead to an outcome that most people today find totally unreasonable or even a violation of basic rights? doesn't that make the whole 'fidelity' thing look like it's just ignoring modern reality?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The perceived conflict between original meaning and modern sensibilities is a central, often unaddressed, tension in constitutional law. Originalists argue that if a right was not understood by the Founders, it cannot be a fundamental right protected by the Constitution. Furthermore, they contend that the Constitution's text itself provides the constraints, and if the text is silent or ambiguous, judges must defer to the original understanding, even if it seems outdated. This adherence to the text is precisely what prevents the judiciary from becoming a super-legislature that constantly reinvents fundamental law.",
      "source": "target",
